I haven't rated anything on Yelp in eons, but felt compelled to after my experience today because this place made me actually mourn the death of customer service--such a bummer! Having tried a very good bread from the Mill (someone had brought me some), I called to see if was in stock and ask a few questions before visiting the bakery
I should've known something was up when it was as though I was totally inconveniencing the person who answered the phone
[note: see Thien's review, several reviews before this one]
I went anyway, with a friend, to buy/eat a loaf of that bread, with almond butter, accompanied by coffee drinks, and to photo/recommend their bread to my network of 600 or so foodies
I asked if a slice of the bread could be toasted
They "don't toast things between 5-6 a matter of policy" (when they switch over from serving bread to serving pizza) and there weren't "enough people there to toast bread

" I don't know if the contamination issue was because of gluten (?) or why they thought they were short staffed (the place was fairly empty, there were 3-4 people behind the counter/in kitchen) but I was so shocked at the rigidity of a bakery whose business is partly based on toast not being able to toast bread (for someone about to spend $20 on an afternoon coffee) or to either explain why and/or lift a finger to accommodate us (e

"we're sorry, but we can at least heat it for you" or "we can slice it and put the almond butter on it anyway"), that I pressed the cashier to understand (I grew up working in the food/hospitality industry in SF and travel widely and this was highly unusual)

I used to love Philz, especially when they first opened on mission, the original location, you would even see Phil himself! I even worked here for a time

First of all, we used so much beans for one cup- enough to make a whole family a whole pot of coffee in one cup- and to cut it we use cream w 60% milk fat! That's the whole reason it's 1)addictive 2)expensive
The difference between a small and a large is abt 3 coffee beans and 1/4 cup more water, so again- great marketing and great way to get that money
All of this is fine and still much better quality then the cancerous fake coffee they sell at nasty Starbucks
Fast forward to years later- the whole menu has been simplified
Everyone who works there hates their jobs, probably bc they're never gonna get paid enough, so that's understandable, can't blame them

Today, I showed up to do write a book report

Not too long afterwards, Manny approached me to tell me that there was a "policy of not allowing laptops after 6"

Now this is his shop, and he can do whatever he likes, but why have such an asinine policy that makes no sense? He went on to tell the 8 or so other people quietly working, reading, watching, talking on their laptops that they had 15 minutes to shut down their laptops

Now it wasn't like he was saying "this space is reserved for people eating dinner", which is what a restaurant would say

It's one thing to tell restaurant goers that the establishment is just for food

RECEIPT SURPRISEWhat floored me to give this rating is actually the new mysterious "Back of House Service Fee" (like Greg B

Afterwards, my friend, who used to manage restaurants, let me know that it's "tip for the kitchen staff" but common restaurant practice is to take this from the normal tip, not force it down your throat with fancy rhetoric

They have one of the highest "SF Mandate Tax" (to cover employee benefits) but it should technically be absorbed into the restaurant cost (imagine the sales tax be broken down like % SF City + % SF County + % CA tax)
What's even more hilarious is that they have one of those receipts with the "check a box between 15%, 20%, 25% auto calculated tip"
And guess what? The % is calculated on the total + sf mandate tax + sales tax + back of house fee (kitchen tip)
So they're essentially asking you to tip on top of tip
This wouldn't have lit me up if it weren't for the fact that it was half empty in there and we had to wave down the waiters to get attention
I love the location of Samovar and the food and drinks are pretty good, but I'm growing frustrated by the deceptive pricing and hidden fees
First, I have found on three different occasions that the price on my receipt was higher than the price on the menu
For instance, the Cold Brew Matcha is $7 on the menu, but is $8 on the bill
They are always shocked when I highlight these discrepancies and only fix it with a one-time discount on the bill - they don't seem to fix the POS
Second, they charge an "SF Employer Mandate," as so many restaurants do

As you hopefully know now, this is not a real tax and restaurants charge an arbitrary amount to cover costs to comply with the new law requiring businesses with over 20 employees to provide healthcare for employees
89 per employee hour for healthcare
Third, they now also charge an additional mysterious "Back of House Service Fee" which is 4% of the total bill
It's unclear what this money goes towards, but presumably compensation for the cooks and cleaning staff
But shouldn't that come out of the revenues? Or the tip?Don't get me wrong - I'm strongly supportive of increasing the wages for restaurant workers
But I would much prefer that the restaurant raise prices than add these hidden charges to the menu
And charging more on the bill than the menu for items is just unethical and illegal

Owned and operated by French expatriates, one of them a fifth generation Baker, it was with heightened expectations that Les Gourmands was entered Tuesday morning, the location at 280 5th Street a bit difficult to access by car during rush hour but at the same time resulting in high foot traffic and fresh selections continuously being baked to replete supplies

Decorated by an artist known as Nairone, his minimalist approach allowing focus to remain squarely on Tarts and Viennoiseries spread across a lengthy counter with names and prices displayed on small stands, it was while perusing the options that a woman identifying herself as Catherine offered guests samples, the corner of an Apricot Croissant crunchy and well-laminated with just a bit of Jam adding sweetness
Located at one of SoMa's most bustling intersections and thus able to justify higher prices than the typical Bakery, $7
00 per Croissant on par with Tartine and more than Neigbor or b

patisserie, it was after assessing the choices that nearly $30 was invested, first bites of the Almond Apricot Tart finding Preserves relegated to the center and the edges a little dried out though the flavor was pleasant
Continuing with Fruit, a $6

40 Chausson Aux Pommes challenging Les Gourmands assertion that everything is organic and locally sourced since the interior tastes like store-bought Pie Filling, it is fortunate that the seasonal Chestnut variety fared much better as a result of toasty Cream inside crunchy, separated layers

Apparently hiring only "zero experience" bakers according to their website, an 18-month apprenticeship intended to train new artisans while also decreasing labor costs, it was while watching one man coach another in back that the "Almond Croissant" was cut in half, the thick Custard not only unexpected but overcooked while the $1 Chouquettes fortunately lived up to their acclaim as one of The Bay Area's best baked goods thanks to a golden exterior flecked by Sugar Pearls and an center that is eggy yet open and light
As locations pop up, the quality of this place is going down
I ordered two drinks: black sesame latte with boba and almond jelly, green tea latte with almond milkBlack sesame latte came with no boba in it

SF is spoiled when it comes to excellent, locally roasted coffee, but this particular section of SoMa is as dense as it gets for top notch coffee options
Sightglass Coffee, Four Barrel at Pentacle Coffee, and Saint Frank are all within a few blocks radius for my daily, within-my-comfort zone fix
East SoMa may have all the new high rises, but you best believe West SoMa is coffee mecca

If you're not coming here every day and just want to check out the location, there a few cool perks (I know, complete mood switch lol):-17ft Ceiling Espresso - Most Blue Bottle locations serve their Hayes Valley Espresso by default
This location serves a special blend named after the specs of this Mint Plaza building

It's a subtle, delicious change especially if you drink Blue Bottle so often that you're almost toooo accustomed to the taste-Siphon Bar - At $8/$14, this is definitely not a daily cup of coffee thing lol
But if you're a coffee aficionado and appreciate the unique methods you can extract a lovely brew then this is something you definitely gotta try
Once(?) they had an extra special single origin coffee from Yemen for $20 so if you're really a bean seeker keep your eyes peeled
Only available between 8AM-2PM
-Nel drip - Blue Bottle has their own custom dripper that they use for most pour-overs, but they also do Nel drips for $10
This cool contraption produces an interesting, more viscous brew
Only 3oz so treat yo self
All things considered, I still come here but not as often  as I could because I drink way too much coffee and have to budget or else I'd be living wrecklessly

Little Sweet was a stop on my way to dinner
I ordered two drinks - a regular milk tea for my man and a White Gourd Milk tea for me
When I went to order I told the guy taking my order I don't really like sweet drinks so I wanted to go for 25% sweetness for my White Gourd Milk Tea

He said the drink isn't that sweet and told me 50% would be not sweet already, and I hesitated and he said 50% is the best since they basically water it down to tone down the sweetness so it won't be sweet
So I agreed for 50% sweetness with his reassurance

For toppings, I asked about white boba - like was it the type that's crunchy, bouncy from other places like agar boba? He said the difference was that it is cooked vs uncooked and that he would not define any of the boba toppings as crunchy or bouncy
why would I want to eat uncooked boba aka tapioca starch balls!? Turns out it is NOT uncooked boba - so do not be alarmed since he wasn't good at describing
After I ordered and tried it in my drink I can confirm that it is actually the clear agar boba balls that is offered at other places
I tend to prefer it to actual boba since it is less sweet and has a smooth bouncy crunchy texture - hard to describe but that's what I would say
PS: If you don't like sweet drinks - DO NOT ORDER 50% White Gourd Milk Tea - it is waaaay tooo sweet despite his reassurances - tastes like 100% sweetness
White gourd lovers - we knowww that the drink is sweet already - so I can't imagine what actual 100% tastes like
If you decide to come here maybe opt for 25% sweetness if you have tastebuds like me! The other order of milk tea was decent but nothing to write home about
Would I come here again? No
But if you do, I hope you get a more helpful person taking your order

Before I go any further, I feel like I need to start this with a disclaimer - I LOVE Philz
Across every single one I've been to (including this one), I've never had a poorly made drink nor have I had to suffer through an awful experience
As such, it feels both weird and uncomfortable to be giving them just a three star review
It's just that, with all due respect, I'm not nearly as fond of where this location is as any of the others I've been to
Like any other fan of Philz that's out there, I've made my way through (most of) their menu and I've found my personal list of go-to drinks
Mint Mojito, Tesora, Mocha Tesora, Gingersnap, Philz Harmonic
any of these will instantly put a smile on my face!  Specifically here, both the Tesoras and Mint Mojitos that I've had from here were just as good as the ones I've had from any other Philz
Unfortunately though, while the drinks and service have been (mostly) fine, I don't particularly enjoy coming here
It's not Philz's fault, and the Tenderloin/Civic Center area is improving, but I hate how I seem to get panhandled every time I come/leave here (sorry if that sounds elitist, but it's true)
What's more, with their spot on Van Ness temporarily closed, the lines here can get longer than normal
Add in how nearby parking isn't always readily available and coming here isn't exactly drama-free
If this happened to be the only Philz that was around, or if I happened to work in the area regularly, I'd be much more willing to endure the hassles in order to get my regular fix of Philz coffee

However, with so many other locations around SF (and the Bay Area) that are much more accessible to where I frequent, I'll save making a return trip here for the next time I have to go to City Hall or do jury duty at McAllister
Which, hopefully, won't be sooner and will be far, far later

You'll love this place if you're a normal-taste-person tho! (Remember I'm a sugar digger) LOVER's LANE, love you forever :)
The first review of 2019 goes to Ritual Coffee Roasters
Ritual Coffee has like 6-7 stores in SF including their roastery
I decided to try this spot in the Castro today
I looked through the list and it was expensive
I was wishy-washy until I decided to get the "cherry bomb
" This drink is a cold drink with ice
It has tonic water, cold brew, and maraschino cherry syrup
It was created by a barista at one the Ritual SF shops
You stir it up
It had a cherry kick with cold coffee and ice
I have nothing better to do than amuse myself with SF cafe creations like the "cherry bomb
" Well, keep on inventing new drinks and people will try it
I have always known about this location, just never had the chance to drop by
For those who may not know where it is, it's kind of hidden within another building, across the street from the main Japan town plaza
It's a modern looking building and will be on the right side when you enter

(The other floors consists of different stores that have Japanese fashion and such, definitely check it out!)My boyfriend and I were the only ones there, so we were able to choose where we would like to sit
The decor is very cute and pink
It makes you feel like you are a little girl playing tea party with your stuffed animals when you are younger
We decided to do the Afternoon tea option for two
My boyfriend and I got two of their most popular teas and it came in a rather large pot with milk (must request)
We also got a 3-tier tower that had finger sandwiches, scones, and other little pastries
The tea was delicious and the best part of the tier foods was the scones
Our server made sure everything was okay and addressed any questions that we possibly had

There were only one or two other parties in the area with us and he attended those tables with a lot of attention as well, even walking a woman who was on her own through their menu, seeing what she was interested in and would like
Overall, a very cute experience! If you haven't been to an afternoon tea, this is a great place to try!

Who knew this spacious spot on the corner of 16th and Valencia was swirling in political controversy? Apparently owner Manny Yekutiel has been the subject of weekly protests over allegations of Zionism

Frankly I find the notion of political protest and point-counterpoint arguments rather refreshing because it's a 3,000 square foot venue for left-leaning activism with a full calendar of community events
Or you can just hangout and have lunch like I did in the bar cafe section upfront
Laptoppers abound here, but I managed to find s small table surrounded by s lot of vibrant local art (photo: bit
There were only four items on their lunch menu and there was a decided Middle Eastern twist to them

I ordered the $11 Cauliflower Salad, which was quite a diverse, colorful plate of harissa-roasted, turmeric-pickled cauliflower florets drizzled with tarragon green goddess dressing and mixed with tomato, cucumber, pickled onions, pepitas, and a lentil quinoa grain blend (photo: bit
To go with it, I had a bowl of the $6 Farming Hope Soup of the Day, which turned out to be a bountiful, lighter-than-expected minestrone (photo: bit
Maybe I should spend more time getting my political consciousness raised
FOOD - 4 stars
Middle Eastern flair in healthy local fareAMBIANCE - 4 stars
true community hangout with a more relaxed vibe for the politically unawareSERVICE - 3 stars
a tad befuddled TOTAL - 4 stars
nice change-of-pace with a higher purpose in the MissionRELATED - Milling about in the Mission? Here's a collection of places I've visited and reviewed: bit
Cute spot for breakfast and coffee! Very busy on the weekends
I stopped by to grab a matcha with oat milk and it was good
Service is great! Wouldn't run over there again just for a matcha but definitely wanna go back to try some of their breakfast options!! Beautiful to-go cups too!!

They have half-off some pastries 4-5pm every day! My friend & I came on a Sunday during around 4pm and tried both Travel Cakes: Gluten-free Chocolate nib and the banana with a drizzle of coconut for $4 total (pretty good)
Both were pretty good but I wouldn't pay full price for them - they were tiny!!!
I think I liked the chocolate one slightly more though
My friend kept pointing out that the banana cake didn't have those black squiggly worm lines things in the bread
o___o take that as you will
They have a thoughtful selection of unique pastries so I'd like to try the others some time
My friend and I ordered the Whipped Coffee, Coconut, and Yuzu dessert to share
I really liked how light the dessert felt and how there where several different textures throughout
The salt in the coconut base was a nice touch since it contrasted all the sweetness in the whipped coffee cream and yuzu filling
The desserts are on the pricier side for their size but you can definitely tell that a lot of thought went into the development of their pastries/desserts
A great study spot, and a lot of people are aware of it, so it can get pretty crowded even though it is pretty big
For my coffee fix, I got a vanilla latte
They unfortunately ran out of mugs, so it was given to me in a to-go cup
It was a little too sweet for my taste as well
Their BLTA sandwich was so delicious though, and their prices are very reasonable, especially if you consider that I'm planning to park myself at a table for a couple of hours
Make sure you charge your laptop though! People battle it out for tables by the outlets, and not all the outlets appear to be working
Popped in on a weekday morning and it was crowded! Even so, the lines moved fast and someone attended to us very quickly
I got the giant white chocolate and valrhona cookie - good texture, not too sweet
I also ordered a flat white to go
Decent coffee to pair with pastries
I really liked the atmosphere here
You should go to this compact coffee hideaway before the influx of badly dressed tourists make it intolerable
Right now the lines consist mostly of young start-up lemmings who already the caffeine is well treated here
The irony is that this closet of a kiosk is located on Maiden Lane between Kearny and Grant, the heart of the tourist congestion zone presuming it has a heart
The young Dutch barista was quite friendly, and there are a dozen hot beverages offered including the $3
25 Cafe Au Lait I ordered which was brewed from Ritual coffee beans (photo: bit

While others took their drinks to go and it was too wet outside to take advantage of their makeshift patio, I sat along the narrow wooden counter where I looked at the vintage cocktail lounge as the staff was preparing to open for the evening (photo: bit
Take advantage of its low profile while you still can
COFFEE - 4 stars
quite smooth as it is Ritual after allAMBIANCE - 3
5 stars
tight inside though hardly anyone sits and drinks their beverage thereSERVICE - 4 stars

Only reason for 4 stars is the value
70 for a large coffee it's pushing the 'OK, that's getting offensive' button
Price not considered I would give it 5 stars
Love their earl grey lavender
Atmosphere is simple and staff are extremely sweet and helpful
I know a lot of my coworkers love their coconut milk latte
Would definately recommend this place if you're just looking for a simple place to get tea or coffee and chill
May the odds be ever in your favor looking for parking though
I was walking on Geary at a godforsaken hour because I had to take my car in for a software issue that affected a lot of that year's make and model

Can you imagine? I never connect autos with software, but considering how I perpetually need the IT help desk at work to help me with my laptop, I get nervous about driving and being affected by some viral bug that will lead to my fiery death

In that unsettling state of mind, I wound up at this tiny corner spot that serves various beverages with or without caffeine, tapioca drinks not before noon (thus the dearth of young Asians at that hour), and a lotta baked goods
Well, the display case looked fully stocked because it was just a little past 7AM on a Saturday morning
It went from empty to all the tables and counter seats completely taken in a half-hour span
Luckily I ordered a $5 Honey Coconut Tea Latte and parked myself at a table before it was taken
That was quite a mouthful of subtle flavors in that biodegradable cup (photo: bit
ly/2HHkhaY), and I enjoyed it while the hipsters gave me small-mouth as they sauntered by
They really need to work on their posture

more like 90/10RELATED - Looking for dining options in the Richmond? Here's a collection of places I've tried and reviewed: bit
A great little cafe situated in one corner of a laundromat
I never thought I'd be a fan of any eatery located inside of a laundromat, but I was wrong
I've been here about a dozen times
The lattes and coffee are solid (good but not the best I've ever had)
The cafe has a wide selection of base goods, including gluten free Dynamo Donuts! The Lemon Powered Donut is amazing
Okay, kick me because I'm wrong
B Patisserie has delightful pastries
It's been a long time since I sat and ate pastries at the cafe
The last time was when there was only their original space
Now that they acquired and opened  up more space it feels like there's more elbow room and I can breath
Yesterday, I met a friend for a breakfast of pastries
Hey, I can't get myself out of bed and home very quickly in the morning so in truth it was closer to lunchtime when we got to the cafe
An open table? I'm surprised! Snapped that up pretty quick and then we were able to sit down and get down to business
The business of eating pastry!I got a chocolate kougin amann and a banana chocolate almond croissant
My friend got a plain croissant and scarfed that down quickly
Appalled (that's no way to appreciate good pastry!) I gave her bits of both my pastries
She's never been to b patisserie before so I'm trying to clue her in on the goodies here
She likes them but then she fesses up that she's on a diet
Say whaaaaat?This friendship is not going to last if she doesn't eat while I sit there like a starved cat with a platter of cream in front of my face
Well, I took away most of my croissant for eating later but that kougin amann was history in no time
Buttery, flaky and just the right balance to the Valrhona dark chocolate
The latter was just too good!Now if only they could tune down the bass to their shop music I'd enjoy my dining experience so much more!
Had a mocha and it was good!  Not syrupy or overly sweet
The food is ok
Have had toast, a quiche, and an assortment of pastries
Nothing has blown my socks off but it is solidly good
Employees are nice and professional and the place is pretty clean
They have delicious donuts in the morning but they go fast!
A very solid latte
I'd say if you're going to do the Zazie wait, a cup from wooden will go a long way toward making it more pleasant
It's also kitty corner from the muni stop and a good spot to get your pre-commute caffeine
This is a unique little coffee shop with Ethopian coffee
Decided to try it before going to Herbst Theater for a free weekend symphony
The Ethiopian pot coffee was something that stood out to me
Definitely is unique and won't be able to find it elsewhere
It's definitely a strong cofee
But it was still pretty smooth
Of course, the bottom of the pot tasted even stronger because the coffee grounds had more time to seep in the water
So you can take more time to drink it because it gets too cold and not taste as good
Just be sure not to drink the bottom
There are a lot of coffee ground at the end
The girl let me try some, but it was a bit too strong for me
Definitely the Ethopian clay pot coffee was a better choice and I'm always in the mood to try something different
On yelp it said they had Wifi here, but they do not! Not really conducive to studying/working here because it is a pretty small space

But, yummy food! There's also another location with the same menu on Fillmore, and a bakery location!About the food~Avocado Toast: Delicious! We ordered it on gluten-free bread, and it tastes just like normal bread! Wasn't a fan of the jalapeños but the red onions, arugula, and egg made for good toppings! The avocado mash was a little bit brown (didn't affect the taste, though)
Black Sprouted Rice Porridge Bowl (hot): This is also gluten-free! TBH, it was pretty bland
We added oat milk, honey, and cinnamon to it to try to sweeten it/add flavor
The granola was good and the rice was cooked perfectly, but I also wish there were more berries on top! Service was friendly and fairly quick
You order at the counter and then sit down

They also have a huge pastry case! I wanted to eat everything in it, but my friend and I ended up sharing the GF peanut butter cookie! It was chewy and had a nice crunch of peanuts spread throughout!If you are gluten-free, Jane is the perfect place to come! About a third of their baked goods are gluten-free, and they have gluten-free bread that tastes just as good as normal bread! Also, the sun shines pretty bright through the windows here in the morning, so if you're by the window, it may get a bit hot
Love this place! Come here for a quick breakfast and coffee every time I'm in San Francisco
Pictured are the waffle and breakfast sandwich (I forgot to ask for ham on my sandwich)
they also have great vegan baked goods!
I dropped by VLT , new location in Noe Valley, exceptional bakery I got  chocolate chip cookies ridiculously good
They have 3 locations in SF, will be back soon to try the tacros it's their croissant tacos" they look yummy may have to go to the ferry building to get those

Samovar Tea is located on the upper terrace of Yerba Buena Gardens and the shop looks to have been designed for you to fully enjoy looking out into gardens with its huge glass walls and covered patio seating
You never have to worry about inclement weather on the patio since it's a frosted glass covered walkway that is a permanent fixture, not a retractable awning or umbrellas
It was a cooler rainy day and we couldn't help but sit on the patio
It was truly one of the most peaceful and serene experiences I've had downtown San Francisco
We enjoyed a pot of blood orange pu erh and a platter of scones while we watched the rain fall over the blooming flowers
The pot of teas are recommended for 1 or 2
You can continue to request more hot water
The server who brought out the tea gave us instructions on how long to steep for and gave us a little background on it as well
For this specific tea, he let us know that the blood orange is pretty traditional in China although the addition of the ginger was not
On the menu it also mentioned that one of the ingredients (?) included wood chips but he didn't mention that one
I'm not sure if there were wood chips included
There were shavings but I'm pretty sure that was the ginger and possibly citrus peel
I mostly tasted the ginger for this tea which was cut with the sweetness of the blood orange
The scone platter was a great accompaniment to the tea
There were three big scones topped with oats and with dried cherries baked into them
The platter came with 4 different toppings including a smooth butter, strawberry jam, blueberry jam, and cherry jam
The jams all brought a lot of sweetness and there were chunks of fruit to be found in each
Samovar is more than just a traditional tea shop as there were a lot of matcha variations which are very in right now, as well as some milk teas
They even have a full page of alcoholic beverages
The prices of the food were a little high but overall worth it for the experience
This is a great spot to do work or study
Plugs everywhere and there's free WiFi
The cafe options are not amazing, but it helps to have something convenient to snack on (like coffee or a sandwich)
I had to ding a star because they charged me for a cup of hot water

Stopped by here for a quick tea fix with a friend! We were hoping to study a little bit but it seems like all the tables were filled up and there were a few bar seats available, so I wouldn't recommend it if you're lookin to study somewhere with avid table space
Most people seemed like they were taking their drinks to go
The ambience was very simple, modern, and clean

I liked how there was a lot of light in the cafe! There's light music playing in the background- it's still very quiet! There's 2-3 baristas patrolling the espresso station & are very willing to help you out and a few pastries they have on display
I saw a few interesting drinks and settled on the honey coconut tea latte ($4
50) with almond milk (+$1
00) which I thought was kinda pricey for just almond milk! The drink was delicious, without being too sweet & just the right amount of coconut flavor without being too overpowering

I liked how the almond milk complimented the latte as well- I wonder what kind of tea they use! Overall a decent place to stop by for a quick drink that's close to USF campus! I'd come back again to try their espresso drinks and maybe swoop a seat to study if I could :D
Intro: San Fransisco has for the past 5-10 years been growing at a very high-speed rate and consequently become overly saturated in new businesses, one of which being boba shops
It seems like nowadays a person could meander to the corner of a block and stumble upon a place that sells boba
Boba Guys is one of those businesses that began during the tech industrialization of the Bay Area
Since opening, they have crushed the boba game and have become an instant go-to whenever I am craving that good tapioca
Drinks: Black milk tea is my choice of order whenever I pass by a Boba Guys
I know, extremely basic but wait a minute, for good reason
I've had the black milk teas of at least 70 different milk tea stores around the Bay Area throughout my lifetime, some good some bad
Boba Guys hits it right on the money and delivers a great standard milk tea
The tea flavor is strong but not overbearing to the point of bitterness, which is probably the most important attribute of any tea drink
The boba is delectably chewy and slightly sweet, adding that fun and interactive part to your boba experience
For sweetness, I like to choose 50% and let the tea, milk, and boba carry the other half of the load
Overall, Boba Guys makes a brilliant black milk tea, one of the reasons why this store has become the boba Goliath it is today
This Philz isn't so spacious, but it has some outside seatings
Also, as same as other locations, their WiFi is good
Of course, the taste of coffee is certainly Philz!! One good thing is this location isn't so crowded compared to other Philz
When you go to the ball park (AT&T Stadium), this location is nice to stop by
Staffs are always nice and helpful to choose your coffee!!
A lovely café in the middle of Cole Valley - you may have to drive a few blocks to find parking
There are some good times to arrive, like just before school gets out on a weekday afternoon (1-2pm)
Come then and you 'll have your pick of tables
However, wait an hour or two and you'll have to contend with crowds of strollers, backpacks and small kids! (Which isn't a bad thing unless they get to all of the cookies before you
) Early in the morning is also a mad rush for coffee
Things to order: we love their egg sandwiches, served all day long piping hot
Try the egg and arugula sando, served warm and sunny side up, with aioli, pesto, and avocado
Their pastries are also delicious, like the chocolate croissant and fresh baked cranberry bread
Do not miss the chocolate sea salt cookies, and always request that they be warmed up
Tastes like it just came out of the oven!! Prices are a bit steep but dems da breaks when you're in SF!!
I love their Kouign Amann! Great spot to come grab dessert and coffee and people watch on a nice sunny day in the Mission!
Think I found my favorite coffee place in the city (for working purposes)
What can I say - it has good coffee, usually flexible seating, decent lighting, and free WiFi
All of which are easy said than done, and this is a total package
It is located in the FIDI next to BlackRock and Nasdaq, and about 4 mins walk from me
Most people here grab seats to finish some work quietly, so I've enjoyed consistent efficiency while being here
I have been to other few around the area, but the interior vibe was too casual/social, and made it hard to concentrate
Happily becoming a regular here!
I tried their Jimmy Hendrix drink, a White Mocha with Lavender
It was so good! I loved the sweet, soothing flavor
My friend got a coffee with espresso and liked it
I thought the interior decorating was great
The customer service was nice, and the girls working there were nice and attentive
They even gave me a little taste of their gelato
I asked for a sample of avocado but she gave me chocolate instead
I didn't have the heart to tell her I had actually wanted avocado, but luckily it tasted really good anyway
Very nice little place
Cool combo of a coffee shop and a video game rental store
The barista was friendly and got my espresso shot out so quick it was like he whipped it out as soon as I placed the order
Espresso was fresh and delicious - not bitter at all
They had a line building up when I came by and since it's not your typical coffee house, I think this indicates the quality and service you can expect to receive here
This place is a cute little cafe on Divisadero
They have a variety food like salads, sandwhiches, burgers, tea, smoothies, and so much more
I got the Petaluma sandwhich and it was ok it lacked flavor so i probably wouldn't get it again
However their side salad is pretty good and i added feta cheese because a salad without feta is like a ceaser with out parmasean cheese
I also got the jasmine green tea and that was nice touch to my meal
This place is warm and cozy and they have WIFI which is a plus! I worked here for a few hours without any disturbance
I will definetly come back
If you're in the area you should check this spot out
A great neighborhood spot for coffee
It's got a good feel to it
Whenever in the area, Philz is my go to spot for a morning coffee
The staff is nice and the coffee is good and strong
It's a place where you could catch up with neighbors and just read or work
On a Friday morning I saw a number of parents gearing their kids up for school with a coffee and a toast
There's a kids reading area as well that my daughter's enjoyed as I enjoyed a very drinkable cup of coffee
I had a dark roast and the kindly staff asked about the sweetness and cream level
Sweet and creamy was my choice and it was just as I envisioned
I really like how the temperature of the coffee is instantly drinkable since why would anyone want to burn their mouth drinking boiling coffee?  Philz gets it on coffee
Solid corner coffee shop
Coffee is good
Coffee is good
WiFi is here
Outlets are available
Outside seating is available
Background music is chill
Staff is great
Ha! Wrote coffee is good twice so it must really be good
Overall a nice coffee place to do some work
They have everything that I want out of a coffee work place, good atmosphere, good coffee, outlets and WiFi
Located on the sidewalk level of the building in which I work, Little Sweet calls to my boba tea-loving coworkers (and there are a lot of them)
In years past I've downed my fair share of the boba, so while I'm the low-carb guy nowadays I did head out with my peeps to celebrate the successful software release
I ordered the black coffee, always a good way to measure a restaurant's way with the little things, while they ordered a variety of the boba offerings
My coffee was marginal, at best, but that's not why you're reading this review
The boba judgement I heard on the way back upstairs ranged from "good" to "pretty good" across all the flavors and mixtures ordered
Something around a 3
5, so let's be generous (they're a new place, after all)
Conveniently located in the downtown tech corridor, near to Union Square and a lot of the shoppings, I'd say Little Sweet is worth a visit
This is such a cute little cafe
I went to go study there, and they have two long tables (no outlets, or not that I had seen) and then more lounge space with small coffee tables
The artwork was also really cool
The space is clean, bathrooms very clean! There isn't much of a selection of different types of drinks to get but their drinks are tasty! Great space to study, and very friendly staff!
The kaya toast is sooo good
It's a fresh baked milk bread topped with coconut and pandan jam
Extremely heavenly! I also got the Moscavado Cookie which has coconut, sesame and moscavado sugar
It was okay but I would not recommend it
I was a little disappointed because the breakfast sandwich they had on the menu didn't have the scallion jam, instead it had fermented chili
And they were out of their not-ube tart because "sweet potato is out of season"
Two items that I really wanted to try but couldn't
One star off because I got a pretty weird vibe from the workers (except the girl, super friendly chick
) The guy who was standing at the cashier area had his back turned the entire time to make drinks and avoid customers
I felt his cold shoulder vibes the entire time I stood there trying to decide what to get
The other guy who brought out my toast handed me the plate awkwardly
He handed out forks and knives to everyone else (who ordered the toast) except for me
Strange
Stopped by for a quick pastry and latte pick me up
Was very happy to have some delicious creme brûlée style latte (more sugary than my average expectation but it was extremely delicious)
The chocolate croissant with churro style sugar also perked me up with each delicious chocolate chip-filled bite
Solid coffee! Really good coffee, rich in flavor and depth, with just enough of cream/milk
Also tried the cinnamon sugar toast which is
BOMB! So good
I would come back whenever I can go get this
It's like buttery sweetness rolled into one
The avocado toast is also pretty good but tad basic for me
Overall great coffee place
The only thing is it's small, very small, and lines can be long and cramped while waiting in the doorway
Line means relatively fast so probably still worth waiting in line
Love what this place is producing
Really like this spot!Coffee: DeliciousService: Super friendly as alwaysAtmosphere: Beautiful spot with great lighting and cute furniture
Wish they had WiFi (some reviews said they have it, but when I asked this past weekend, they said they did not)
Lovely little coffee shop tucked away in sunset
It's pretty easy to miss, just look out for the wooden sign hanging outside
Another one of those instagrammable places, I recommend the titanic latte if you want the aesthetic pic - it comes with a huge square marshmallow and also has  chocolate spread in it
My friend tried the mocha latte, which was also really good
Drinks weren't too sweet and there wasn't a line when we went on a Sunday morning
Wouldn't expect to study here though, they have wifi but very limited seating
Prices are what you expect for a higher end coffee shop, when I went the titanic went around 6-7 dollars
They have a selection of baked goods too, I'll try them next time I drop by
Parking's difficult, circle around on side streets for parking (we parked closer to GG)
If I'm ever in the Rincon Hill area of Soma I like to stop by this cute little neighborhooody fine chocolate/coffee-stop
The chocolates are small for $2
75 but they pack a lot of flavor and have pretty designs on top
There are some unique flavors, my favs are the tea ones like the Duchess of Earl or Jasmine tea
In addition to chocolate pieces, they have hot drinks, chocolate bars (you have to try the potato chip and pretzel!), and gift box sets
They can do customized logos on the chocolate pieces in bulk, so it's a great idea for corporate events
This is a great place if you work around here otherwise it's hard to get to and not open on the weekend
Great place to stop by before / after hanging out in Golden Gate Park or the Haight
I recommend the latte here bc of the strong coffee flavor that comes through
Bonus points for the good latte art too
I would def come back w/o hesitation
The coffee was really delicious, so I have to give them stars for that
However, if you are looking for a place to work, this wouldn't be my first pick
The actual place is very small with just a tiny little table to work
You can work at the tables outside though, but that's pretty weather-dependent (and knowing sf, it's most likely to just be cold and windy)
Plus, no outlets is a thing
But if you're not coming to work, hit this place up for a good coffee
A hip and cute coffee shop in inner sunset!I come here because I love the cozy and warm vibes this place give! Though it looks small, it's spacious and I always happen to find seating right away
My favorite is Spaniard which is Spanish latte with condensed milk
It's bit sweet but pretty delicious! You must give it a try because it will warm your soul :) Their matcha latte is pretty good but just standard
Highly recommend this place especially on a cold windy day!
Just stopped in here for a quick cup of coffee and the place was super cool
Wish I had spent more time here with my laptop and a good book because it is totally the shop you want to come to for all the coffee place cozy vibes
Good people watching spot from the window and friendly staff
Oh and their coffee was excellent too! Like most places nowadays they had your non-dairy milks, always appreciated and some food options too that I didn't dabble in but definitely would next time
Tried tasting as many different coffees from various places in San Francisco as I could during my first visit and this place definitely had one of my favorite cups!
Good bubble tea for sure, but worth waiting in line for? Probably not
I visited their Union Square (Stockon St) location since my hotel was only a few blocks away

I decided to see what the hype was all about, since I had some time to kill
They have an efficient ordering system, with someone taking orders from people in line

Boba Guys has some interesting drinks that I don't often see at other places
I opted to try one such drink: strawberry matcha latte
It was good
Creamy and strawberry with some bitterness from the matcha
Good, but not wait 15 minutes for good
Overall, a Boba guys is an excellent bubble tea spot
Just don't expect much more than that - bubble tea
And probably not worth waiting in line for
The pastries will make your brain truly explode
GO EAT ONE NOW
GO!However, NOT a fan of the fact that they have no "ice", and therefore: no iced coffee drinks, whatsoever
For those of us who only drink iced coffees: no bueno
Bonus: the backyard is a beautiful, garden patio with metal trellis-like tables and chairs
FEELS FANCY LIKE IM IN FRANCE(?)
close to home
simple and convenient for me whenever I want something to hold in my hand while I'm walking (unless if you let me hold your hand or your girlfriends hand instead)
I change my mind,
actually I'd rather hold the cup of unsweetened matcha tea with grass jelly than your girlfriends hand
simple joy
thank you very much

Main differences between this Philz and the other ones is that 1) extremely family friendly with a play corner for children, 2) street parking isn't too bad, and 3) tends to be semi-full (most likely because it's family friendly and not bring your laptop and work)Service and drinks are the same as other Philz locations
I usually come here if I'm going to just talk and hang out with a friend or two
I tried once coming with the intention to work but the children friendly corner was too much of a distraction for me
Very cool cafe! I also love the selection of pastries they have
The pastries & donuts are a bit pricier (normal hip-SF-bakery price), but they're totally worth it
My favorite is the pistachio blackberry croissant! It has the perfect balance of very different flavors: crispy, sweet, fruity, and nutty

Yum!~~~ UPDATE~~~ Seems like they no longer have the pistachio blackberry croissant, but they now have ham and cheese croissant that's also pretty good! The pastry is slightly glazed in between the flakey layers, so it gives you hint of sweetness along with the savory flavors
(It also looks pretty since it has sprinkles of dried flowers and veggies on top :P)
Good ice latte, perfect for chat
Not a really good place to work, no outlets, no wifi and loud music
Great coffee, warm space, open, comfortable
The music is pretty much always too loud
Like, yell across the short table at your friend too loud
Five stars on days they tone it down
Great people watching spot, as well
I came here the other day to kill some time before picking my girlfriend up from an appointment
I ordered a bone dry cappuccino
It came and the barista knew it wasn't really dry so she insisted on making me a new one
Granted the second one wasn't very dry either I appreciated the effort and did love my coffee
Worth the hype!! After seeing so many yummy post and ppl raving about this place I made this a priority reservation for my next trip to the city
Since I had a bigger party (5 ppl) I made reservations, but we did go at an off time during the weekend, (around 3PM) and had no wait
Located right next to the infamous (& also yummy) Kitchen Story - this place looked really tiny, but was actually long in layout and pretty spacious
Really cute casual decor with a Farmhouse vibe, and service was quick/nice/efficient overall
Of course, I already did my yelp research ahead of time & knew what sweets to order - but pretty much all the desserts looked tasty & had an asian influence in flavahhh + modern plating/decor
which were both beautiful and unique
Let's Dig In:(1) Matcha Molten Chocolate Lava Cake - FN amazing!!! Beautifully warm and chocolatey cake with perfect gooey texture + filled with a tasty strong matcha lava
Soooo yummyyy!!(2) Boba Thai Tea Bingsoo - good but a tad bit too sweet, shaved ice had good texture, Thai tea flavor was strong, boba had a nice chew
Good bingsoo overall
(3) Mochi Garlic Toast - this was shockingly one of my fave things here
The bread was perfectly toasted and lightly garlic flavored which (SOMEHOW) went amazingly well with the sweet nutty mochi flavor - pretty much perfect blend of sweet and savory
(4) Young Coconut Pandan Crepe Cake - not the best crepe cake, but still really freakin good
Flavors were amazing and perfectly light in pandan flavor + also loved the coconut toppings and side of coconut cream
The texture of the crepe itself was a little too soft compared to others I've had, but flavors made up for it

(5) Matcha Latte - tasty! Lightly sweet, creamy, and super strong in green tea flavahhh - just the way I like it!(6) Hojicha Latte - lightly roasted flavah and a lil more milky than the matcha latte (which isn't my preference) - but still good
(7) Cafe Latte - okkkk overall, coffee itself was pretty light with a lot of milk, not sweet at all since you can add sugar yourself
Could do without this next time

Wonderful environment to destress! Would've been helpful to have a sign up on the wall for what we can do in the meantime before going into the kitty room and what the protocol is before going in (taking off shoes/hand sanitizer) because it was a little awkward to stand around not knowing what to do with myself
Just a small thought :)
The problem with me going to bakeries is that I tend to get too much and always shock myself at the register
I would only regret not getting it to see how it tasted
In any case, this bakery always has a line but does move relatively quick
I think there was  ~25 people ahead of me and I got to the register within 15 minutes
You pretty much order on your way to the register
Along the way I got:[1] Chocolate chip cookie ($4) - It's huge, flat and delicious
I didn't think about getting it but 2 groups that were ahead of me got one and so I figure why not! No regrets! I even picked up a bag near the register
25) - Expensive but this is probably one of the best ones I've had
The inside is more cakey then custardy like I'm use to but the zesty cake flavor was soooo good and the outside wasn't that bitter
If they have any I highly recommend it![3] Gougere ($4
25) - It's like a hollow cheese bread
It looked different on the inside compared to other pictures I've seen on yelp
[4] Frangipane Tart (~$8) - This was pretty good
I like the crust because it's very croissant like and the berries wasn't overly sweet
I think next time I will try the hazelnut one
I was just thrown off because the hazelnuts on top looked like corn nuts
[5] Baguette ($6) - Expensive as well but pretty good if you pair it with cheese
I prefer the softer baguettes like the ones you get with banh mi and at the Asian stores you can get them for a $1!I would have gotten a sandwich but I heard it takes about 15 minute to make
It feel very cramp and there's a fair amount of seating but not enough for my party
There's also outside seating but it was a cold day so I opted out of the sandwich
Maybe next time! I will definitely be back for the morning bun that I heard so much about and the pies looked amazing! So many good things to try and with such a small wallet I can only get so much
Had the absolute hot chocolate here!!! Have yet to try the coffee ironically, but I'd really come here just to get their hot chocolate--wow
Cafe Lambretta is a convenient place close to AT&T Park
My dad and I stopped by on our way to the A's-Giants game and were surprised to find that the restaurant was only half-full
We both ordered sandwiches and they came out in good time
I personally recommend the hot pastrami, by the way
It's a short walk from AT&T Park and a great spot for relaxing with friends or by yourself
One of the best Cafe in SF!! A little pricey, but it worth for the quality
Their cappuccino is the best
I love their hot Chocolat as well
Another reason for me to go there is that they sell the baked goods from Starter Bakery
Almond croissant and chocolate kouign amann are the best!! As for the service, it depends on the staff
Some are super friendly, but some are not
Goooood coffee, nice space
Only thing is that it's pretty hot inside and although there's a lot of space, there's no WiFi/barely any outlets to use
I also attended their first coffee tasting today and learned a lot about where they get their coffee beans and even got to Skype with the farmer in Colombia who harvests their beans
It was pretty cool

For $20, we got to learn a lot about the source of their beans and even got to try their pastries and the first tasting of the coffee! We also got a free bag of coffee beans as well and a cute pin that gave us a free cold brew next time we came
Overall so worth it if you love coffee/cafes like me
great place for a quick coffee run- they offer a variety of croissants and baked goods
the location is right off of having street next to whole foods- a super convenient location if you are driving or taking the muni
staff was really sweet and welcoming
only room for improvement is the seating- i wish there were more tables to sit at to chat or study
otherwise great place, check it out!
A super cute little nook in the Mission serving breakfast sandwiches, tater tots, pastries, and oatmeal
They also have French toast on the weekends
I got the Breakfast Little Sandwich and it was amazing - I liked that the ingredients were wrapped up in the egg to prevent spillage
The bread was also so perfectly soft with a light crisp
My boyfriend got the almond fresh toast which was perfectly crispy and the right amount of sweetness
We also got the honey and cinnamon Tater tots which were an interesting take
I don't know if I would order again but I enjoyed them!
5 stars if they didn't mess up an order
Lots of good coffee, tea and drink choices along with sweet and savory breakfast and lunch options
My brother in-law tried the coconut milk iced coffee but it tasted off so asked for something different
When he asked for a latte they made it iced (but that wasn't what he ordered)
Oy veySome tables inside and several outside when the weather is good
Would definitely come back as the employees are nice and coffee (I had a cappuccino) is good
Wonderful environment to work or chat!  Large area with many tables and high ceilings
We enjoyed tea though there appeared to be a good coffee and food menu
Came here on a Saturday morning and there was a line out the door

The line moves at an okay pace, but gosh the lattes are good! I highly recommend stopping by this place to grab a latte before you go to ocean beach or lands end! Patio area shields you from the ocean winds
Love having Vive la tarte in Noe Valley, enjoy the ambiance, the food a just about everything about it!
My only complaint, and why it's not a 5 star,  is that the special croissants that are available at other locations of Vive La Tarte for some reason are not available in Noe Valley
The first week they had some of these special croissants, banana etc but since then they've only offered the basics which are not nearly as much fun
Considering how much we enjoy strolling the Castro, Jamie W
and I rarely find ourselves walking on 18th Street west of Castro Street

I just think people like us get used to their routines, which is my roundabout way of saying we had no idea this shop existed until we saw the sandwich board that announced free truffles inside (photo: bit
Now why would we pass up an opportunity like that? I wanted a little caffeine after dinner, so the idea of buying a $2
25 cup of coffee seemed reasonable to me for a mouthful of sweetness (photo: bit

Now choosing which truffle turned into quite a challenge as the display case was full of all sorts of variety from peanut butter to cinnamon dark chocolate to rum coco to even vegan truffles (photo: bit
I settled on the hazelnut once which was covered in them in pulverized form (photo: bit
Oh yes, that was certainly a pop of goodness well worth the mediocre, overheated cup of coffee I bought
Should I come back for the $33 40-piece gift box or the $45 60-piece gift box? Such decisions should be made when I'm standing on a weight scale, so I remember how ridiculous that question is
TRUFFLE - 4 stars
lovely mouthful there though the coffee needs to be thrown outAMBIANCE - 3 stars
just a little shop, nothing moreSERVICE - 3 stars
oh so quietTOTAL - 4 stars
another one won't kill me, right?
We stumbled upon this place while walking around the Mission and it was such a nice surprise!The brunch was great and the services amazing
There is a back room we're you can sit and read books or be on your laptop which is also pretty! Highly recommend!
Love local breakfast spots! This one is so incredible that they are open wayyy past breakfast time! Lovely location, with ample seating and space for a bustling city
I can't speak for their famous baked goods, but I can sing the praises of their dragon fruit chia bowl
They had a solid selection of bowls and other healthy choices to choose from, but k was drawn to this striking dish for a refreshing midday treat
It was perfect

Not too hot or too cold, it was full of flavor (and antioxidents!) The toppings were delicious- I wish there were a few more! A bit skimpy on the chia and berries, I like my bowls very textured, but it was still yummy! One star off for the service, we had a small group of 5, and the staff were more intent on moving us up and out then making sure we had an enjoyable stay
Also, the prices are ambiguous when ordering, and were (onviously) rather expensive
Clarity on pricing would be great! Otherwise, a lovely experience
Would love to go back and try some of the baked goods!
One of my favorite Philz stores in SF
The store is beautiful, well organized, pleasant to lounge around and do work in
What REALLY makes it for me here is the baristas
I especially love Adam and Natalie, they're both super fun and always makes sure my drinks are right! I like the music they play and for being a busy coffee shop, the bathrooms are relatively clean
I love the mint mojito, the ginger snap (both iced), Tesora, Philtered Soul etc

As for food, I like the vegetable quiche (be careful, it's super hot!) This would've been a 5 star review, except sometimes it's slow and it seems like they don't have enough people for the volume of customers they get
It's a pretty big Philz RIGHT across the Ferry Building, so sometimes it gets quite busy (even on the week days)
It's one of my favorite boba places in the city
I do recommend it
I like the location by Octavia
The only problem is finding parking
The drinks are good
I like coming here for coffee! Different vibe because it's also a bar (at night, with a dj) and gallery, so it's not your typical setup (some high tops, some coffee tables, benches, etc)
You'll see people catching up, working, or just checking out the art
Have you ever wondered how much caffeine is in a matcha?  If so, do like we did

Wander in to Stonewall Matcha at 4 pm on a Sunday, enjoy some tea and some tea-infused desserts, and then when everyone you went in with is up at 2 am and not at all tired, it begins to sink in that matcha has a lot of caffeine in it
A LOT
Lack of preparation aside, if you pace yourself (and we did not since our drinks and dessert all were chock full of matcha) Stonemill Matcha is good alternative option for a tea spot in the city
Our group liked the almond milk matcha
The warm ginger matcha latte was even better, with a nice shot of fresh ginger syrup

The interior is minimalistic, from the Scandi- light woods, to the sparce artistic signage and limited, well-selected baked goods in the case, to the steampunk tea making areas, to the simple black pottery
Desserts here are a mixed bag, our favorites being the matcha parfait (sundae) and the strawberry roll cake
Their matcha cream puff looks beautiful, but the cream puff shell was extremely hard and off putting
The matcha pie looked appealing, a fluffy matcha meringue , but the person in front of us got the last slice of the day
Food items are slow out of the kitchen and timing is off
We had received and finished our teas before desserts had even arrived at the table
All in all, a good option if you like matcha (and don't mind staying up late!)
Good place to study or get work done
Foods pretty good as well, and they have beer and wine:) gets crowded though
I've come here twice where there is no table available, but after a few minutes something seems to become available
Really like this place
Really yummy, but didn't satisfy my sweet tooth
( I had the ice cream btw)
One this is certain though, everything on the menu looks really pretty, so it makes for a nice thing to post on your ig
Pretty chill environment , this coffee shop has kind of a neighborhood flair
The staff are really helpful and very informative
If you are a hipster that likes to pop up at coffee shops with your mac book and pretend to look important , this is defanitly the place for you
I typically like to see if coffee shops are dog friendly and this obe didn't really have that feel
The shop is located behind a huge tree in front of the building so its kinda hard to find
Great coffee shop, very posh and upscale
At nearly $6 for a latte, it's EXPENSIVE; however, my latte was silky smooth and made to perfection with love by a passionate barista who really knew what they were doing
I would come back if I am in the area and in need of a kick, though it's unusual for me to justify $6 for a latte regularly
Great coffee shop! It's located in the heart of Castro and has beautiful window seating for people watching and a nice view of the district
Right now, I'm sipping a Gibraltar by the window
It tastes great and perfectly blended with the milk

My barista did a great job! This coffee shop is great and I recommend it for those living in the area! Weaver's is a good neighborhood coffee shop to go to! Before the gym or after, make sure to stop right in!
Friendly staff and great & creative mixed coffee drinks
I love a few of their coffee blends and dislike others, but they have plenty to choose from
Only downside is that ordering drinks takes awhile
If you see a line longer than 5 people, it's at least 10m until you get your drink
Affogato and the waffle was what I ordered
Omg, so good! Although the wait was really long for the waffle, it was totally worth it
It was crispy yet fluffy with a slight hint of sweetness that is perfect with coffee
The affogato was good also
I do prefer it in a cup vs the bowl they gave me though
It made drinking the espresso a bit difficult as the bowl as shaped a bit funny
Totally need a waffle and coffee shop around where I live though!
Decent atmosphere, beautiful hand painted murals in Renaissance/Art nouveau style
Not bad, but very beige
Lots of beige
Standard coffeehouse menu
Nice staff
It was my first time going there today as I live a couple blocks from there but was very skeptical trying it based on recent reviews
It seems cozy and a nice cozy neighborhood cafe
The girl working today seemed nice enough
Wouldn't say she was pretty friendly but she didn't seem rude either
I got vegetarian bagel and their cream cheese tasted very basic but okay
Coffee is definitely very good
Beautiful workspace with lots of large communal tables perfect for awkward side-by-side working and chatting with strangers
For whatever reason, this store seems to accumulate a lot of heat
probably a combination of location and lots of natural light
Pretty popular spot but I've never had trouble finding a seat
Coffee was good, but it was pretty expensive for a pretty small cup of cold brew ($4
Their cups did not seem regular size and I really needed every last drop of caffeine
Also, their bathroom is like the bathroom design of my dreams
I'm pretty sure they got custom wooden accents made (like there is a wooden cover built into the wall and also a wooden holder for toilet seat covers
because clearly that was necessary)
I was also super digging the matte white wide subway tiles
And Aesop hand soap to top it off
I ordered the Matcha Toffee + boba at their standard sweetness (75% I believe)
The tea itself was delicious and creamy
The boba soft and gummy
The toffee wasn't my favorite in the drink

On its own it is tasty but they just put a lump of it on top of the drink so by the time I finished my tea the majority just sank to the bottom with the ice rather than really mixing in or adding flavor
Maybe I should have mixed it up better before drinking, but seems like they should mix it into the milk if that's the case
I love the matcha and would order again but would skip the toffee next time
Came here this week to quickly work before closing time- great space with different seating but access to outlets

Oat milk latte was DELICIOUS and the two peeps behind the bar were fun and great! However, would appreciate some cocoa and cinnamon to add! Will def be back for late night caffeine hits and work space
Had a great cappuccino here on my first stop of delicious coffee spots in SF
Cute space with friendly staff
The line was out the front door but moved quickly
Great place to work or catch up with a friend: free wifi, good coffee, friendly staff, not to crowded!
25/5Came by on a Friday morning around 10am for a quick breakfast
Luckily there was no line and I was in and out in 5 minutes
The shop is small though they have 3 large benches outside for seating along with their extras setup (water, cream, sugar, napkins, etc
Unfortunately no shade or outdoor heaters available
Parking in the area is mostly street and can be difficult
Easy to access by MUNI though
Service is really friendly
They have a small menu but if you're coming for baked goods you just have to look on the rack to see what they have
I got the following items:1) Everything Croissant: The only item I semi regret
It's still pretty good but it can't compare to the other two items
The top layer is very flaky but most of the flavor is there so once it flakes off the remainder is pretty flavorless
It's not an overly buttery croissant so the inside is airy but otherwise a sticky doughy texture
There's a bit of filling consisting of cream cheese and green onions but it's not enough to carry through the whole croissant (though personally I also use a ton of cream cheese on my bagel)
I'm also not a huge fan of the grainy texture cream cheese takes on when it's baked
5/5)2) Sauerkraut Smoked Cheddar Peppadew Tart: I wasn't sure how this would work out in pastry but I absolutely loved it (given I am a fermented food nut)
In terms of texture it's similar to the croissant
Not buttery but fluffy with a flaky (though less than the croissant) top coat
I wish the filling as a bit more dispersed but overall I loved it
It's almost like an elevated version of nacho cheese and kimchi
The sauerkraut peppadew combo is very kimchi-like though a touch sweeter
This with the smoked cheddar made for a perfect balance
The bread itself is quite sweet compared to the salty spicy filling so the extra doughy-ness works a bit more favorably here (4
25/5)3) Twice Baked Pistachio and Blackberry Croissant: Like a cross of Seattle's Bakery Nouveau twice baked chocolate almond croissant and Arsicault's almond chocolate croissant but with fruit
The texture if just like Bakery Nouveau's a sort of heftier crust with crunchy ridges
The filling has that more grainy sweet paste texture like Arsicault's but it offsets the sweetness with the nutty toasty pistachios and the tart blackberries
In principle I am still a chocolate over fruit girl but damn this was good (4
75/5)Overall I really enjoyed my visit here
While I've had better croissants elsewhere I loved the unique flavor combinations they offered here
I definitely want to come back to try some of their hot food options or their kimchi toast (they serve this at room temp but you can get it heated up)
---The Re-return: Twice Baked Pistachio and Blackberry Croissant if you are a fruit person; otherwise go for Arsicault's chocolate croissants---
Tea was almost cofeeish in some areas
Boba is very nice flavor and texture
The sweet milk was the highlight, I would make myself sick on it if I could
The pastries alone would bring me back
Coffee is good, they have house made vanilla and caramel hard to find in SF
Owner is responsive and kind and just gets it
Pastries are the bomb and interior sparkling clean
I got the cold brew
It was strong but I wish they have other alternative milks
They only have almond milk
The service was really quick despite a line
They have compostable straws and containers, which I really appreciated!
Never did I expect a place like this tucked into a corner in the Japan Center, it feels like a world away
Tan Tan is a quiet oasis in the hustle and bustle with the feel of a British teahouse
The furniture and linens are beautiful, the glassware is gorgeous and the environment is tranquil
We came in, ordered at the counter and the woman working there told us to sit and she would bring them to us
I noticed that everyone else there had some sweets but since we had just come from the YES event at Matcha Cafe Maiko, we were very full and sugared out
Next time, I totally plan on getting something to snack on as everything looked delicious
After about 5 minutes, the woman brought us our drinks in REAL GLASSES (my favorite!) I had a cappuccino and A had some genmaicha tea
My cappuccino was really good with just the right amount of foam and A's team was great as well
We lounged around for a bit just enjoying our time and the conversation
I do not think this would be a great place to come and work as I don't think there was WiFi but it is not meant to be that kind of coffee shop
As such, this felt a bit stuffy but honestly, I really enjoyed it
It was a bit expensive for a coffee shop but when you consider how peaceful it was and the service aspect, no complaints
I will definitely come back when I am in the area and have some time to sit down and enjoy a hot beverage
The coffee flight idea is really cool! In the flight I had the latte with their storemade almond macadamia milk and it was really good
I didn't care for the iced coffee on the flight
The rest was good
I came near closing time so I would love to come back to try their lavender latte
Still love the place, and the coffee is so good, but why, oh why did they have to change the bread recipe they use for the toast! It is not as it used to be, toast is to dry
Small bakery in the corner street
Reasonable wait time
Most reviews talk about good food but poor service, but we were lucky with both
Chocolate croissant - 42
Salmon and egg scramble over croissant - 4 1
The croissant was delicious
We ordered it at the front bakery
I think there was an entire bar of chocolate in the croissant
The egg scramble was very well cooked and soo soft
The salad had a mustard dressing which was delicious as well
My friends had the croque madame And eggs Benedict they said it was really good, unfortunately I did not have a taste
Good place to come for brunch, I would come again
Also the service was great but the presume it was because it wasn't too busy
This is just down the street from our favorite brunch place so we like to grab a coffee while we're waiting in line over there
The decor is nice and cozy with a really unique collection of VHS horror films on the back wall
The coffee is good and the staff is friendly, including an African gray parrot
On our way to the Dicken's Faire we stopped here for breakfast
Delicious food and Mexican coffee was spicy and tasty
Very small place with only two tables, but seats outside
They seem to do lots of take out, they are fast and reasonably priced
The French toast is amazing!
I had a couple of hours to kills in FiDi before a client meeting so I decided to park myself at the Coffee Shop
I decided to get the cold brew ($4
50) and asked for single pump of vanilla flavor but was told that apart from simple syrup they don't have any flavor shots
The barista was friendly which is the case in most of the coffee shows in FiDi except Peets
The cold brew had a clean non-acidic taste as expected but it lacked any real depth of flavor and felt monotonous
It did the job of keeping me busy for an hour or so and I was on my way as a happy customer
5 stars rounded to 4 is how I'd rate this place
I have gone to this little coffee shop a few times
My first time was really nice and the taste was very fresh
Since then, I think the quality has gone down a bit
It's always busy when I have gone and sometimes the barista is nice but not always
I do see a lot of regulars that do go to this coffee shop more than the crappy Martha's
I always get the mocha with their dairy free milk which the oat milk is my favorite
I don't like how the oat milk is a hit or miss there as the last few times I have gone, they didn't have any oat milk
I think their drinks are on the small side but I think it's because it's more a hippie European coffee shop
I feel like they should get a larger size and still have their traditional regular size

The price has recently gone up as well which I know how expensive it is within the neighborhood but I'm not sure how fast I will be back for a cup of coffee unless I'm really craving a mocha and they have oat milk
I never tried their doughnuts/sweets there so I'm not sure if it is good to try or not
I would definitely pick this shop over Martha's as I just despise Martha's coffee/mochas
An adorable cafe with a unique layout
Has enough space to study or work while sipping on their yummy mocha! Lots of natural light and even outdoor tables and benches are available if you want to enjoy the sun when the weather gets warmer
Who needs a rebel within when you can be a bear without? There are far too many ways to enjoy a soft boiled egg than hidden inside a muffin
But a nice travel cake or cocoa nib financier in sizes petite enough for a baby bear? That's a good deal at $4 each
Add on a green oolong tea and there is even room for a $9 green pill pastry from the glass case with lime leaf custard, mango cream, and vanilla sponge cake for later
Is it America's Best $15 Road Trip Adventure Meal? A burger and beer at Black Sands Brewery in the Lower Haight might be better
But for earlier hours, tea, travel cake, and a pill for the road just might make a nice runner up
Why let wolves and rebels have all the fun? Put the bear in the Bear Republic by opting out of the soft boiled muffin mayhem
Tea and tiny cakes are classics for a reason
And green pills are meant to be taken orally once every 24 hours
I am visiting San Francisco from Dallas, TX and this is a very cute coffee shop! They have gotten on the toast band wagon
I had the sliced banana, honey, cinnamon & almond butter
The only reason why I didn't give them five starts is that there is not a lot of room to sit
There is a small bar height table with stools that looks out to the street!!! I highly recommend this place the coffee & toast I had was awesome
I told my friend who lives in the city that it's a must try!!!
They have oat milk! I live nearby and this is my favorite spot to get an oat milk latte
They have great pastries as well - an assortment of croissants, scones, and vegan donuts
It's probably not the best spot if you're looking to get work done as it gets pretty loud, especially on the weekends
The line can also get very long on the weekends, sometimes almost out the door
But the coffee is great!
Stopped by to get a Shakerato
Small 8 oz cup of 2 shots espresso (I asked for 1, because I want to sleep tonight), cream, and some brown sugar
I got the Scratch Caramel, asked for light sweetener
Didn't really taste any caramel, but tastes strong, rich, aromatic, and creamy
A great midday pick me up
However, it's HELLA EXPENSIVE
75 for a couple sips of espresso
Super cozy and sweet place
Coffee is amazing
The hot chocolate is great too
Will come back some time
A friend and I were browsing for a study spot and luckily stumbled upon Rise & Grind! For a Tuesday afternoon, it was pretty crowded but we were lucky enough to snag a table next to an outlet
I ended up ordering a biscoff cookie butter latte and a breakfast sandwich! It was pretty hard narrowing it down to these too because there were so many great options
The cookie butter latte was tasty and not overly sweet but I wish it had a bit more cookie flavor to it
The sandwich was delicious, messy, and very filling
I kind of wish this was served on a plate rather than wrapped in foil since we ordered for here but it honestly wasn't too big of an issue
My study experience was good here and while it was a bit loud, it's nothing a little music can't drown out
The wifi was down for a moment but was pretty fast otherwise
Excellent chai! I tried their golden latte-- it was nicely steamed and had a spicy kick
The turmeric powder DOES settle so I would recommend not taking the last sip in the cup
Price wise, it cost me a over $5 with tax for the smaller size
In general prices here are on the higher side
The cafe has a nice modern industrial feel
There is one big tall communal table in the center of the cafe, with some high top tables along the windows and two seater tables against the walls
It looks like a decent place to work
There is a self serve water area and a co-ed bathroom (that needs a code to enter)
Randomly walked in to get something to drink and discovered Equator Coffees and Teas
It is a nice coffee shop to sit and watch the people go by on Market
They offer indoor and outdoor seating which gives you options while you sip your coffee and people watch
There is also free wifi if you want to have a place to get a little work done
Since it was a beautiful and "warm" day for San Francisco, we skipped the coffee and decided to get some iced teas
We ordered the iced black tea and the iced rooibos chai latte
The black tea was refreshing and the chai latte was creamy and full of spices
The service was friendly and helpful when it came to deciding what to order
Next time I will have to try the coffee
Brazilian cheese bread comes with every hot drink?! Sign me up!So good
Cute little find
Worth it to stop in and check it out
Not a huge variety but its a cute, quick stop
Plus, who else has brazilian cheese bread?

Based on my first trip I am happy to come back!I only got the ham Vietnamese sandwich but it was exceptional! Fresh as morningtime bahn mi in Chinatown Looking forward to trying the coffee drinks

It's been eleven long years since my first review of Spike's, and I was a gushing li'l Yelper at the time dramatically comparing the service one receives there to the feeling of being kowtowed at a high-end Japanese department store

? Well, Jamie W
and I were back at Spike's after a long absence just because I was looking to have some hot liquid in my body after a brisk walk over the Swish Alps

50 cup of Rooibos (photo: bit
Jamie, never a fan of hot liquids, went with the $3 Ginger Peach Iced Tea

We decided to replace our collective sweet tooth with subtle eavesdropping skills as we listened to an awkward blind date at the next table where the more interested guy kept laughing like a hyena at anything the other one said

TEA - 4 stars
nice loose-leaf qualityAMBIANCE - 3
5 stars
tiny space, crowds quicklySERVICE - 4 stars
good but remember that I am a curmudgeonTOTAL - 4 stars
good to be back, Spike
This place is hippppp y'allllllll
I wasn't sure if I was going to coolness poisoning upon entering, however, I survived and was won over by the experience

iced
latte with espresso
enough said
It's very Southern Marin Hip, backed up against Proof Lab Surf Shop and sharing a parking lot with a Surf Camp right off the freeway on shoreline highway on the way to the beach

Such a cute little hole in the wall Family Owned Cafe! I have lived across the street from Piccolo Pete's for almost a year now, and today finally had a little time to check it out! Service was quick and friendly
We ordered: Mr Fancy Pants toast - garlic, olive oil, Brie Cheese, mushrooms, and honey
SO SIMPLE
SO GOOD

Walked past this place on my way to brunch and just knew I had to come back and pick up something for later! The place was pretty packed and so there was no place to sit (not really an issue for some since I was getting to go)
I settled on a morning bun which came out to $4
75 which si honestly think is a bit expensive but wOW was that a good pastry! It was nice and flaky and super decadent
I wish there was a bit more lemon flavor though, that really would've helped to cut through the sweet buttery flavor
