I have a Sunday ritual of visiting a different coffee shop every weekend and enjoying an Americano and a good lunch
So I thought I'd start leaving reviews on these based on three criteria (5 being the best): Food, ambiance, and extras
You're probably wondering why I'm not grading on coffee? Well because I'm not an expert, but what I do know about is the above topics
Food: 4They provided quite a vast selection of food options, from sandwiches, salads, baked goods, and small bits
All of which were made to order
I ended up having the chicken pesto sandwich that came with a salad
I do have to say it was satisfying, however, I feel like the chicken might have reheated, prepackaged meat and not sure if they made the pesto in house
The salad was just greens with a little bit of dressing
The soft ciabatta bread and cheese was what saved it for me
Again, overall satisfying, but which it was fresher ingredients
Ambiance: 4This shop is super cute and if you're looking for a neighborhood vibe, this is it
The shop had huge windows that let in a lot of light, which I loved! So I was sure to sit by the window on the bench that spans across the wall
Though there were cushions on the benches
they were worn out and flat so wasn't the most comfortable
The staff was really nice and helpful when ordering and delivered my food to my table
The cafe is made even more charming with the trolly that rides by from time to time
It was pretty quiet despite the trolly, which is was surprising
Overall, very cute and welcoming cafe
Extras: 5So one of my pet peeves is when you go to a cafe and they have bad wifi, Nook had very strong wifi which was easy to connect
However, on the weekends, there's a 2-hour limit, which really wasn't an issue for me, since I only stayed that long
They also had a good amount of outlets to plug into against the wall which is nice to see
Parking wasn't too bad either, considering the location
I feel like anything past Van Ness, parking get's difficult, but I was able to find a spot just up the street
Luck? Maybe
Overall I really liked this shop and highly recommend checking it out
I went around noon and it wasn't super busy, so might be a good place to meet up with a friend for lunch or work on your laptop to get somethings done
This is most likely my favorite coffee place to grab a good drink
I usually drink tea and the Philz tea is delicious
The quality sometimes varies based on who makes it and the customer service isn't too great, probably the location
I love Philz and I'm sad they no longer have a location on Van Ness
I walk to this location instead now
The mobile ordering app makes it very easy to pre-order, walk-In, and leave without much social interaction
This saves me a lot of time!
Empanadas are pretty good and service was awesome but lacking on the churros and unfortunately no WIFI
I get it, this place isn't known for Churros but just saying it's meh and basic
So definitely skip that on the menu

However, the empanadas are pretty darn good! I wished I could try more! Also, I really wished they had WIFI, what coffeeshop/cafe doesn't have WIFI? how do you expect people to gather here if there isn't any
Anyways, HIGHLY recommend for Empanadas!
Sure seems like the hip joint to be at if you're on the beach and want that good cup of coffee or a nice little snack this is a place to check out
Seem to be busy most of the day because in the middle of the afternoon it was still busy

But worth the wait oh, and we were happy with what happened as far as our coffee and snacks give it a try see what you think if you want fancy move on if you want a nice little Beach Cafe to get that coffee this is the place

My sister and I stopped by today, and we loved our food! I ordered the ginger matcha latte and matcha cream puff, and she ordered the matcha latte and matcha almond croissant
It was all so good!  I will say that the ginger in my latte was a little strong, but that may just be because I ordered it lightly sweetened
We went there at about 10 am on a Saturday, and the line wasn't too bad!  We had enough time to peruse the menu and narrow down our options (we wanted to order everything)
The staff was incredibly friendly and served us quickly
I will say that I'm not sure how this place would be considered a good study spot
The restaurant was super crowded and all the seating is hard wooden chairs, but if that's your jam then go for it!
Cute little spot
I came in on a rainy Saturday morning so I found parking easily but Home was still busy! I got a birthday cake latte to go and egg in the hole with brioche toast
The latte was quite sweet and the toast was pretty decent

I would come back if I was in the area and try something else out on the menu
Love This Philz Coffee In SF's Potrero Hill Hood
in marked contrast to the Philz here in Sacramento that is much more
When I'm visiting in Potrero Hill, this is my 1ST choice to come to for coffee, and I have to give thanks to the Yelp app, since I found this spot with it
THE SETUPSituated just to the right of the I-680 Freeway, this was only a 10-minute walk from buddy's home where I was staying
It kinda is in an industrial area, of sorts, but this neighborhood has a lot of work/living loft arrangements and a lot of businesses in old warehouses
The advantage of this is that this Philz is quite spacious!  Lots of room inside
And lots of room on the outside front patio
I would have preferred to have been outside, but I specifically posted here for a few hours to give my iPhone X a chance to update with the new iOS 12
1 operating system without interruption and I wanted my laptop to be juiced up for the entire time, so I chose a table with outlets

COFFEE & QUICHE!While here let my laptop and phone update themselves, I casually wrote some Yelp reviews, and enjoy some of the taste treats here:* I had their coffee "Ambrosia of God" - a delightful flavor
What I am put off by, though, is their strict barista regulation of all "input" into the coffee
By that, I mean, THEY also put in the sweeteners, and THEY also put in the Creamer, and THEY also put in any of the powdered flavors you want in your coffee
com/biz_photos/phil…   I like doing that myself, no offense
* I also had their artistic looking vegetable quiche - it was stylish & tasty, if a bit more pricey when compared to other coffee shop quiches I patronize
But after all, "WiFi" IS a filter I include in my search so I would have been sorely disappointed if they hadn't
DECOR!Both beautiful art and contemporary decor make this a pleasant place to gaze upon while contemplating what to write
Their lighting is also cleverly created to show "Love"
com/biz_photos/phil…THE LOWDOWNThank you, Philz, for providing a nice spot to both relax and get some work done, while enjoying some coffee & taste bites in the meantime!
Pretty standard Philz spot
Nothing really against Philz coffee it just never has been my thing
I also can't tell if SF has too many people or not enough comfortable sit-down cafes

waiting

, front row for people watching

so go ahead, half of you call me a snob and the other half call me an environmentalist

I walk 4 blocks and they are closed
I'm sure they are good so
4 stars

taking a coconut almond milk latte and a chocolate cheesecake cupcake
few minutes and ready
space is small and tables are cramp, but finding a place to sit

tasty latte with subtle coconut flavors
highly recommend getting it

delicious thick chocolate cheesecake inside
moist and good
Blue Bottle is (admittedly) overpriced and extremely slow, but they are extremely consistent in the quality of their coffee
Amongst the different high end coffee shops in the city, Blue Bottle still reigns as one of my favorites (both for mochas and lattes)
This one usually has a line out the shop since it's in a high-density working area
There's two payment areas but I've usually only seen one person behind the register, so the line moves pretty slowly for the high volume of patrons who frequent this shop
It probably doesn't matter in the end, though, because the space behind the counter is extremely small and the rate that the drinks are produced is alarmingly slow
There's usually a couple baristas for espresso drinks, and one doing the drip coffees and tea
I will likely still come to this location, but make sure you allot yourself up to 15m (or more) minutes during peak times, like in the mornings before work
This sweet little neighborhood place is friendly even if you have no dog

Enjoy!!
Really good spot

Very SF
Just discovered this tiny place as I was walking down Divisadero

Good for a bite and to get a bit of work done

Excellent mochaWell tastingWell texturedLoooove that crispy fresh coffee bean roasting smell in the airPerfect combination of chocolate and coffeeTook half a star off because of lack of sitting space but hoping the owners/managers can address that soon
A few more tables and chairs will definitely pull in more folks to this quaint Will be back for coffee
You got great competition here!!
I went to Ritual when I went to check out Flora Grubb Gardens

there is only a few bar stools in terms of seating, but you can take your coffee into the garden and sip among the succulents and other green things

I just wanted something refreshing
The Cherry Bomb hit the bill

It is a fruity, refreshing jolt to the system that will wake you up and put a pep in your step

After your of buying $5 coffee at Starbucks, I didn't bat at eye at the $6 price tag

A bought a nicely packaged bag of thumbprints for a gift
my Mom offered me one later that day,The cookies were just the right size to hold an entire mini peanut butter cup on top

if you live strong coffee balance by serene settings and some good people watching try this little slice of awesomeness in Bayview
Possibly the only person to have never tried their egg-in-a-muffin but still leaving a review for the ambience - it was refreshingly not crowded during the Sunday brunch hour
I originally came in to study - which was doable but do note NO OUTLETS
I would highly recommend for any coffee dates or chats with friends
Sightglass is one of the top quality coffee brands in the city and is definitely a favorite of mine
I like this mission location a lot just because it is more of a to go place with some indoor seating and no wifi

I did like how sightglass encourages customers to bring their own cups/jars etc
The only thing that kinda grossed me out was that there was a horseshoe fly buzzing around in the pastry display and that turned me off from buying anything in there

Coffee: 5 starsService and communication: 2 stars They say this is the OG Philz so that's exciting

I ordered this toast with poached eggs

Not one of them disappointed
Give this place a try for great sweets and all Day energy with there bright green Matcha

Tried both hojicha latte and matcha latte but wasn't special

This place is located under the NASDAQ company building

Down the street, you'll also find Equator Coffee under the Linked In building filled with Linked In workers
This was my first time exploring coffee shops that were located in company buildings

Spacious seating

I have been a fan of Weaver's for years before I went to their actual coffee shop in SF
I would order it online

Nice little coffee/tea shop with adorable seating area upstairs

, soy, oat, coconut, walnut, rice, macadamia

Excellent tea, just did a tasting, but be prepared for some Pacific Heights uptight gong fu

Tried this place out for a quick breakfast

Great Service and even more delicious treats
Got the following items: instagram
com/p/BwoDj7Bh…The Kaya Toast is probably what's everything to rave, colorful, instagram friendly, and delicious

Awesome local coffee shop

e the coffee cola and the pour over coffee hit the spot

I have two coffee scoops at home
One is made of plastic and came free with my Hario V60 ceramic dripper
The other is metal and was purchased at Williams Sonoma when, as a graduate student, I was feeling flush with cash after my monthly stipend arrived
Most of the time, the luxury-model stainless steel scoop sits in the back of the cutlery drawer
It's smaller than the plastic one and takes three scoops to reach 25 grams of whole beans on my digital scale
The plastic scoop usually needs just one
Occam's Razor - the caffeinated kind, mind you - in action
When I brought my first bag of "las Nieblas" home, I rummaged around the cutlery drawer for the metal coffee scoop
I carefully cleaned my Zassenhaus manual grinder by running some uncooked rice grains through it and wiping it clean with an organic cotton cloth
I reread the pourover chapter in Grounded: The Fundamentals of Brewing a Delicious Cup of Coffee (2018)
It was just before sunrise on a Saturday in early May
Quietly, so as not to wake my companion sleeping in the other room, I lit an oak fire in the fireplace
I put Disc 1 of "The Definitive Vince Guaraldi" on the stereo
I measured and ground 25 grams of coffee and poured 400 grams of just boiled, charcoal filtered water into the dripper
A hand-thrown ceramic mug was pre-warmed and ready
Over the sink, I did a high pour into the mug so that a beautiful bunch of coffee bubbles formed on top
I walked to the hearth and took my first sip as the crackle of burning wood accompanied "Cast Your Fate to the Wind" on the stereo
A dense fog was rolling in off the Pacific, and the redwoods were dripping steadily as a golden-hued early morning light began to brighten the room
I stood in front of the fire sipping that cup of "las Nieblas" until it was completely empty
I almost never do that in one sitting
In a million years, you will not get any more "Saint Frank" than that

What would Uvaldo Moreno have said if I had measured out his magical beans with a scoop made of mere plastic? Or sipped it from a dirty travel mug with the scent of past pourovers still in it? Señor Moreno would not have been pleased, nor his two sons, Milton and Alexi, whose coffee parcels are named "las Nieves" ("the snow") and "las Nubes" (the clouds") and also are roasted here at Saint Frank
How do I know all this? Because Saint Frank told me! It's all on the cards with pictures of the coffee parcels from which the beans have been harvested
I didn't just buy a bag of freshly roasted coffee beans that day
It's more like I adopted them, like in those old TV ads for Save the Children
Ever heard of an heirloom coffee varietal called Parainema? Me neither! That's because it's probably unique to only one section of Santa Barbara Mountain, Honduras
You can try that one, too
Benjamin Paz grows that one
Saint Frank buys it directly from Benjamin and ships it to San Francisco, where it's roasted here in SoMa
Plus a bunch of other single origin coffees, each with their own personalized backstory and "mud to mug" micro-narrative
Even the espresso machine here - an Italian made custom VA 338 "Black Eagle" - has a backstory
Barista Championship
That's right: the exact machine
Not the model! The actual machine that won it
It's like having your honey lavender latte made by Mary Lou Retton
That croissant you're eating? Jane made that
Jane who? Jane the Baker, obviously

Haven't you been paying attention to Saint Frank and his spiritually-tinged planetary mission "to inspire joy, connection, and meaning in coffee with simplicity and courtesy"?I don't know exactly what "fourth wave" coffee culture would look like
But Saint Frank ain't no third wave wanna-be
Maybe in Menlo Park, where Facebookers can slurp up "the Fog," "the Snow," and "the Clouds" in a single sitting while trolling your latest posts for harvestable data
Or on Polk Street, where Saint Frank's original cafe is still located
But this here is a roastery
Customers do not come first
If it feels a bit like an artisan's workshop, that's because it is
The fact that you can even sit down while you drink is a major perk
bag of beans to go ($19-21), and they'll throw in a complimentary cup of filtered drip - your choice
Except that you can't drink it in front of an open fireplace with redwood rain falling on the rooftop
Unless you actually happen to be Uvaldo Moreno or one of his sons
Then, you are welcome to join me for an early morning fireside pourover
I'll make it for free and serve you sourdough pancakes with fresh Seascape strawberries to boot
Together, we will light a votive candle on the breakfast table for Saint Francis
Uvaldo, my friend, even a multi-billionaire like Mark Zuckerberg can't offer you that

friendly service
cute decorations
unique pastries

Located on Mission Street (a few blocks north of the 24th Street BART station), Grand Coffee is a small shop that offers your usual coffee/espresso based-drinks
They also offer non-coffee beverages if that's your jam, but my guess that if you are choosing to visit a place with "coffee" in the title, you are looking for a cup of Joe
I've tried their regular coffee and their Americano, and I thought both were well done
The Americano was smooth and not overly acidic, and the coffee was good even without cream and sugar
They offer Cuban pastries as well, and while I haven't tried them, I thought it was great that they offered something different than your usual cafe snacks
The service has been consistently friendly when I've visited, and there's a casual and welcoming vibe to the place that makes it very appealing

5 hours because there were no dishes on the table when I first arrived and left

Amazing!

Probably not an old business can say it's new and really good place to go on weekdays , so many people recommend me to visit them and finally I did and which makes me happy to listen to other sometimes as well

Love

Updating this review to 5 stars

' I knew suddenly I was in the right place

I really enjoyed their breakfast bagel with bacon

Me and my friends had stopped by after a nearby museum

I have found my favorite coffee shop in San Fransisco! Situated next to Dolores Park, this is such a delightful German inspired coffee shop and just sitting it reminded me of the amazing times I had in Berlin
There is just such good energy in this coffee shop, Aesthetics very crisp and welcoming, the service is amazing, and the coffee is so wonderful especially on a nice sunny day
A lot of their pastries are pastries you would not find typically in America
I had one of their soft boiled eggs with muesli and it was very delightful
It's also very quiet inside and you can do a lot of work inside if you need to
I just love all of the German decorations as well
There's something so nostalgic about this coffee shop and if you are in San Francisco, I highly highly recommend eating here
The next time I come, I want to try some of their German dishes
